.] [masculine].
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="360" pageNumber="361">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lindroth" authorityYear="1954" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Bracteomimus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="360" pageNumber="361" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<pageBreakToken pageId="360" pageNumber="361" start="start">Bracteomimus</pageBreakToken>
</taxonomicName>
Lindroth, 1955a: 49. Type species: 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Stephens" baseAuthorityYear="1828" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Bembidium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="360" pageNumber="361" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="chalceum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="360" pageNumber="361">Bembidium chalceum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Dejean, 1831 by original designation. Etymology. From the generic name 
<taxonomicName class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Bracteon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="360" pageNumber="361" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="360" pageNumber="361">Bracteon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
[
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="360" pageNumber="361">q.v</emphasis>
.] and the Latin 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="360" pageNumber="361">mimus</emphasis>
or the Greek 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="360" pageNumber="361">mimos</emphasis>
(actor) [masculine].
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="360" pageNumber="361" type="diversity">
<paragraph pageId="360" pageNumber="361">Diversity.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="360" pageNumber="361">Nine North American species, one of them extending into northern Mexico.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="360" pageNumber="361" type="identification">
<paragraph pageId="360" pageNumber="361">Identification.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="360" pageNumber="361">Maddison (2008) revised the species and provided a key for their identification. Some of the species are very difficult to recognize on external characters and the male genitalia must be examined.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
